{{Music of India}}

'''Nacni''' means ''female dancer'' in north Indian languages. In the east-central [[India]]n states of [[Jharkhand]], [[West Bengal]], and [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], the term '''nacnī''' (lit. "dancer" pronounced NUCH-nee) refers to female performers who sing and dance professionally in rural areas, accompanied by male ''[[ḍhulkī]]'' and ''[[nagarā]]'' drummers who move around the stage with her.<ref>{{citation |first=Carol M. |last=Babiracki |journal=[[Society for Ethnomusicology|Ethnomusicology]] |title=Between Life History and Performance: Sundari Devi and the Art of Allusion |year=2008 |volume=52:1 |pages=1–5 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |first=Marcia J. |last=Citron |journal=Music and Letters |title=Women's Voices across Musical Worlds (review)  |url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/music_and_letters/v086/86.3citron.html |year=2005 |volume=86 |pages=508–512 |doi=10.1093/ml/gci090}}</ref> Women who perform as ''nacnīs'' are considered "kept women" and are usually paired in an informal "marriage" with a male manager and dancing partner, typically of a higher [[Indian caste system|caste]].<ref>{{cite book |first= |last=Feldman & Gordon |year=2006 |title=The courtesan's arts: cross-cultural perspectives  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-iuYBiOkRgC&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118&dq=nacn%C4%ABs#v=onepage&q=nacn%C4%AB&f=false |pages=118 |location=New York |publisher=Oxford University Press }}</ref><ref>{{citation |first=Carol M. |last=Babiracki |journal=[[Society for Ethnomusicology|Ethnomusicology]] |title=Between Life History and Performance: Sundari Devi and the Art of Allusion |year=2008 |volume=52:1 |pages=3–6 }}</ref> In this pairing, nacnīs are thought to embody the goddess [[Radha]] while the male dancing partner is a stand-in for [[Krishna]]. The performers are considered [[Dalit|out-caste]] and in many ways transgress usual Indian caste and [[gender]] distinctions both on and off stage, taking on a certain power role among their "fans" and often engaging in "typically male" behavior, such as drinking and smoking.<ref>{{citation |first=Ragnhild |last=Soren |title=Gendered Images of Music and Musicians  |url=http://www.musikforskning.se/stmonline/vol_2/andra/Sorin.pdf |year=1999 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |first=Carol M. |last=Babiracki |journal=[[Society for Ethnomusicology|Ethnomusicology]] |title=Between Life History and Performance: Sundari Devi and the Art of Allusion |year=2008 |volume=52:1 |pages=5–6 }}</ref> This style of performance is rapidly disappearing.<ref>{{citation |first=Rita |last=Feliciano |journal=Dance View Times |title=Kathak at the Crossroads: Innovation Within Tradition  |url=http://archives.danceviewtimes.com/2006/Autumn/02/sfletter15.html |year=2006 |volume=4:35 }}</ref>

